Reference-contexts: Previously, these measurements have been made using a number (23) of vertical argon flashers deployed around the Flys Eye detectors <ref> (Bird et al 1995a) </ref>. These flashers project collimated beams of ultra-violet light into the atmosphere at thirty minute intervals. These beams of light are scattered and viewed by the Flys Eye detectors. <p> These beams of light are scattered and viewed by the Flys Eye detectors. However, the position and trajectory of these flashers is fixed, allowing only a partial picture of the atmosphere to be derived. More recently, a LIDAR system <ref> (Bird et al 1995a) </ref> has been developed for use with the High Resolution Eye Detector. This device has a variable trajectory, but is restricted to a single location (Flys Eye 2) due to the physical size of the components and the precise optical alignments required.
